<div class="f14 metric" style="color:#656668;display:flex;"><img src="/assets/images/calendar.png" style="height:12px;margin-top:auto;margin-bottom:auto;"><span class="updateDate">&nbsp; Updated on 11/03/2019</span> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="/assets/images/updated.png" style="height:12px;margin-top:auto;margin-bottom:auto;"><span class="readTime">&nbsp; 1 minute to read</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><br><div class="mw-parser-output"><p>Service Management Automation X dates are all stored using a <a target="1" rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_time"><span class="s1">unix timestamp</span></a>, these values need to be converted using the ‘format’ function in order to display the date in a user-friendly manner. The dates are stored in the local server time, so a time zone offset needs to be used to display the date in local time. For example, if the server location is in London, England, and the user wanted the time to appear as the local time in Moscow, the time offset between London and Moscow needs to be added to the now() function. Three hours is 10800000 milliseconds, so the rule to add this would be: <b>${format(now()+10800000,'long')}</b>. The long parameter always adds the time zone of the server, in the below case PDT. Using the short parameter removes the time zone.
</p><p><a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="xc bre ex4 1.png" src="/mediawiki/images/1/1a/xc_bre_ex4_1.png" width="1660" height="166" data-file-width="1660" data-file-height="166"></a>
</p><p>The entry in the comment would appear as follows:
</p><p><a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="xc bre ex4 2.png" src="/mediawiki/images/7/78/xc_bre_ex4_2.png" width="1278" height="109" data-file-width="1278" data-file-height="109"></a>
</p><p>Using <b>${format(now()+10800000,'short')}</b> instead of ‘long’ would result in:
</p><p><a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="xc bre ex4 3.png" src="/mediawiki/images/5/52/xc_bre_ex4_3.png" width="1202" height="100" data-file-width="1202" data-file-height="100"></a>
</p><p><br> 
</p>
